{"chapter": 8, "question_id": 35, "text": "Pratapaditya's reception of Ramchandra Ray is characterized by indifference and a lack of royal fanfare. He refuses to arrange musical welcomes, provides a smaller-than-usual welcoming party, and provides a small elephant, leading Ramchandra to feel deliberately insulted. Upon their meeting, Pratapaditya is calm and detached, interrupting Ramchandra’s speech to attend to administrative matters before dismissively telling him to go to the inner quarters.\n\nIn contrast, within his own entourage, Ramchandra is deeply offended by this treatment. He questions his own status relative to Pratapaditya, asking, \"In what way am I lesser than Pratapaditya Ray?\" and resolves to behave in a manner that will prove to Pratapaditya how \"great a man\" he is."}
